### 4. Difference in PID Tracking: Regular Workers vs. Commanders

| Aspect | Regular Workers | Commanders |
|---|---|---|
| PID filename | `worker-N.pid` (unpadded) | `commander-NNN.pid` (zero-padded 3 digits, `printf "commander-%03d"`) |
| Glob pattern used | `${PIDS_DIR}/worker-*.pid` | `${PIDS_DIR}/commander-*.pid` |
| Progress tracking | None beyond PID | Separate `swarm-state.json` + `child-agents.jsonl` per commander |
| Failure handling | Agent script exits non-zero; pane stays alive (`remain-on-exit on`) | Same + Python writes failure state to `swarm-state.json` |
| Fleet record | `fleet.json` → `role: worker` | `fleet.json` → `role: commander`, includes `telemetry_contract`, `progress_dir`, `swarm_scale: ss-250` |
| Sub-process PIDs | Not tracked | Not tracked by launcher — commanders internally manage their Squad Lead and worker PIDs |

The PID file *mechanism* is identical; the naming, count cap (≤5 commanders vs. ≤20 workers), and surrounding telemetry are the differences.

